  "topic_name": "Moment of Force (Torque)",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The moment of force (or torque) is the turning effect of a force about a pivot point. It is calculated as the product of the force and the perpendicular distance from the pivot to the line of action of the force. The SI unit is Newton-meter (N·m). Moments can be clockwise or anticlockwise. According to the principle of moments, when a body is in equilibrium, the sum of clockwise moments equals the sum of anticlockwise moments. This principle is used in levers, seesaws, and many tools like spanners and door handles.",
    "rules": [
      "Moment of force = Force × Perpendicular distance from pivot",
      "SI unit of moment is Newton-meter (N·m)",
      "Moments can be clockwise or anticlockwise",
      "Principle of moments: Sum of clockwise moments = Sum of anticlockwise moments (at equilibrium)",
      "Larger perpendicular distance means greater turning effect for same force",
      "Levers use the principle of moments to multiply force",
      "Door handles are placed far from hinges to increase moment",
      "A couple consists of two equal and opposite parallel forces"
    ]
  },
